{{ Infobox scientist | name = Nicholas Tucker | image = <!--(filename only)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | residence = [[Lewes]], [[East Sussex]], [[UK]] | citizenship = [[English people|English]] | fields = [[Educational psychology]], [[Cultural studies]], [[Children's literature]] | workplaces = [[University of Sussex|Sussex University]] | alma_mater = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = [[Bernice Rubens]] | influenced = | awards = | footnotes = }}
'''Nicholas Tucker''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] academic and writer who is an honorary Senior Lecturer in Cultural Studies at the [[University of Sussex]].
He was educated at [[Burgess Hill School (Hampstead)|Burgess Hill School]] in [[Hampstead]], [[London]], where his English teacher was briefly [[Bernice Rubens]].<ref>Nicholas Tucker [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20041028/ai_n12812138 "Obituary: Bernice Rubens",] ''The Independent'', 28 October 2004. Retrieved on 22 July 2007.</ref> A former teacher and then an educational psychologist, he has had a long association with the [[University of Sussex|Sussex University]], having lectured in [[Educational psychology]] and [[Cultural studies]] and [[Children's literature]] at the institution. He was a Senior Lecturer in several of these disciplines.
Tucker is a regular broadcaster and participated in ''[[Stop the Week]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]].<ref>[http://www.roughguides.com/website/travel/AuthorPage/author.aspx?authorID=134 Rough Guides page]</ref> He contributes to ''[[The Independent]]'', the ''[[New Statesman]]'', and ''[[The Times]]'' supplements.<ref name="BearneWatson2002">{{cite book|author1=Eve Bearne|author2=Victor Watson|title=Where Texts and Children Meet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2o6EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR11|date=4 January 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-62443-0|pages=11}}</ref> He lives in [[Lewes]], [[East Sussex]] and has three adult children.
