{{Infobox Museum |name = Oman Children's Museum |image = |imagesize = |caption = |map_type = |map_caption = |latitude = |longitude = |established = 1990 |dissolved = |location = [[Sultan Qaboos Street]], [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]] [[Oman]] |type = Children's human science museum |visitors = |director = |curator =Samirah Ahmed al Raisi |publictransit = |website = }}
The '''Oman Children's Museum''' is a children's [[science museum]], located near Qurum Nature Park off [[Sultan Qaboos Street]] in a white-domed building in [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]], [[Oman]].
The museum was established by the Ministry of National Heritage and Culture and opened on November 17, 1990 by Sultan [[Qaboos bin Said al Said]] on the 20th National Day celebration in Oman. The museum has 45 exhibits and two demonstrations and comprises {{convert|10000|sqft|m2}}. It was the first science museum in Oman and is visited by around 50,000 visitors annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontariosciencecentre.ca/sales/portfolio/oman.asp|title=Oman Children's Museum|publisher=Ontario Science Centre|accessdate=January 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name="Wonder world"> {{cite web|url= http://www.nizwa.net/oman/explorer/places/childmuseum/childmuseum.html|title=Children's wonder world|publisher=[[Oman Observer]]|accessdate=January 18, 2009}} </ref> The museum is currently run by a former school teacher, Samirah Ahmed al Raisi, who has run the museum for over six years.
The museum addresses the scientific ways of human life and the exhibition section is divided into three parts; The Human life, Physics and observation which investigates the progression of science through the ages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiarooms.com/travel-guide/oman/muscat-museums/index.html|title=Muscat Museums|publisher=Asiarooms.com|accessdate=January 18, 2009}} </ref>
The museum has many hands-on displays. These include experiences of a fake [[electric shock]], trigger a [[lightning discharge|lightning bolt]], launching a [[hot air balloon]], photographing your own shadow, and sending message through a whisper dish.<ref name="Wonder world"/> There is also a display named "Eye Spy", which is series of perception panels with illusions designed to offer some insight into how your eyes and brain see things differently.<ref name="Wonder world"/>
